    <item>
      <title>Analyzing the New Variant of Redline Stealer</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/analysis-reports-blog/posts/new_redline/</link>
      <pubDate>Sat, 28 Mar 2026 21:57:44 +0530</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/analysis-reports-blog/posts/new_redline/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h3 id=&#34;introduction&#34;&gt;Introduction&lt;/h3&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;The Redline stealer has been a prevalent malware used to harvest sensitive information from infected systems. Known for its predictable decryption tactics, recent updates indicate a shift in its approach to config decryption. This post explores those changes in detail using a sample available from MalwareBazaar.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;h3 id=&#34;sample-details&#34;&gt;Sample Details&lt;/h3&gt;&#xA;&lt;ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Source&lt;/strong&gt;: &lt;a href=&#34;https://bazaar.abuse.ch/sample/796b5d63c93d71012e8a8e8a7bd9e1290ca3963b7f6c78c3cdd0023cfebe9eab/&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;MalwareBazaar link&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Observation Date&lt;/strong&gt;: 2026-03-28&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Claimed Malware Type&lt;/strong&gt;: Redline stealer&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;/ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;h3 id=&#34;observations&#34;&gt;Observations&lt;/h3&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Earlier versions of Redline relied on a consistent config decryption method:&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>My First Post</title>
